items.name: Princess Doll Likeness
items.description:
AnimeGenius - Realistic AI Art Generator Online is recommended

【Model porter】

Semi-realistic Korean style baby face LoRA

This LoRA model is based on a semi-realistic Korean style baby face. If you also like this model, welcome to download and use!

In the training set, each image has undergone a lot of retouching, and a total of 282 pictures of Korean girls have been obtained. In order to achieve better results, I used image generation technology and StableSR redraw processing.

All images in the training atlas are vertical and contain only the upper body. Due to the large body proportions, it may not work well if you try to draw a full body image. Also, if you're doing an HD restoration, you might not get the best results. Therefore, this model is more suitable for face modification and repainting.

Here are some recommended models and settings:

Recommended model: MajicMix Realistic V6

Recommended LoRA weight: 0.6-0.8

Resolution: 512*768

Positive words: 1girl, breasts, solo, swimsuit, bikini, long hair, outdoors, looking at viewer, beach, day, cleavage, upper body, blue bikini, bangs, parted lips, collarbone, ocean, black eyes, realistic, black hair , lips, medium breasts, bare shoulders

Negative words:

NSFW, low quality, worse quality

Note that in order to maintain the shape of the face, the example image does not use high-definition restoration, but uses Tiled Diffusion + ControlNet Tile Model to perform a secondary zoom-in with a redrawing range of 0.6 when LoRA=0.6 is turned on. Therefore, the resulting effect is slightly different (but not drastically different) than on the website.

items.name: Plane Helper
items.description:
Introducing Plane Helper! A multi-concept LyCORIS (trained as a LoHa) for v2.1. Plane Helper is trained on around 2300 images of 71 different planes. I would like to share my training process for anyone interested in learning about training a multi-concept LoHa on complex concepts. This is by no means meant to be scientific, but to help others who might be facing some of the same roadblocks I did.

Dataset:

I've created a data table that contains all 71 plane types in this model along with their respective key tokens which can be viewed here:

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1N7o4pc9mGyYSYIoeD4fU_WpO_2tL_JfKDETOJPVQw18/edit?usp=sharing

The project started after realizing how bad 2.1 was with planes. They would always come out with wings in the wrong places, or extra wings, and not very detailed. Sometimes nothing more than a blob of pointy geometric shapes. I aimed to do something about it. So I started out by grabbing about 130 images of cool looking planes and running them through a batch interrogator for captioning. I trained with Kohya and realized no matter how much I trained, I would still get the same issues. I felt the issue was I had too many different objects and was confusing the LoHa by not differentiating them and just calling them all planes, or jets. So I decided I was going to identify each type of plane and inject their names into their respective captions.

I didn't know much about planes, but I wanted 2.1 to be able to make awesome images of them. So the process of running each image into image.google.com and identifying them all was a tedious but necessary exercise. I ended up with 71 different plane types. So instead of picking 2 and moving on. I thought I would see what this LoHa type model was made of and continued to build my dataset with at least 30 images of each plane type and train them all into 1 LoHa. There were some plane types that I could not get 30 decent images of, however I decided to leave them in the dataset because the ultimate purpose was to train a model on planes in general and it might help to keep them in there. By the time I acheived this goal, I had about 2300 different images total for 71 different plane types all organized neatly in their own folders. Then came the captioning process.

After running these through batch interrogation using Captionr, I googled each plane type and made an excel table with the name and brief but detailed description of the aircraft. I then brought each folder into the Dataset Tag Editor extension one by one and proceeded to clean up the captions and inject the tokens from the excel table I made into each one. I decided to add a debug "CHV3CPlane" token and a "CHV3CTiltRotor" token for the tiltrotor planes (because they are very different shapes) into each caption as well. These debug tokens work great for making unique planes as well. I also allowed for weighted captioning so those debug tokens, along with the plane type identifier tokens were weighted. For example a caption might look something like this:

"(Hawker Hunter), transonic jet-powered fighter aircraft, Hawker Aircraft, Royal Air Force (RAF), Avon turbojet engine, swept wing, (CHV3CPlane), a plane is flying in the air, swiss, low level, man, viewed in profile from far away, switzerland, illustration, overhead".

After this long and patience testing process, I now had an acceptably decent dataset to begin training with.

Repeats:

I initially set the repeats for each folder to 5 but some plane types had a smaller amount of images in their dataset than others, so I did a rough balancing where the planes with a higher amount of images ran for 5 repeats, where as a set with few images might have ran for 10-15.

Training method:

I went about this project in a somewhat unorthodox way. For a dataset so big, I naturally had issues with overfitting. For LoHa a network dim of 8 is recommended but I changed over to 32 to allow for more training space. I went through a few phases trying to find the best settings that would allow me to train for more epochs before getting too burnt up. The original source model was v2-1_768-ema-pruned, however with each training run, I would merge the LoHa from the previous run into v2-1_768-ema-pruned and use that merge as the source model for the next run. The theory behind this is that it would gain some sort of extra knowledge from the previous run and give it a little bit of a head start. This theory needs more testing. Preferrably on a smaller dataset. After each training run, I would also merge the old source model that I merged with the new merged source model and then use that as the new source. I would also use Extract LyCORIS LoCON to extract a lora from it. This particular model is 4 LoHas from 4 different training runs (all on the same 71 plane dataset) merged together and extracted.

Training Specs:

I won't get too in the weeds with training specs. Instead I will post where I found the best settings to be for this particular project and point you to 3 other guides that go through everything in much better detail.

THE OTHER LoRA TRAINING RENTRY

https://rentry.org/59xed3

LoRA Training Guide

https://rentry.org/lora_train

RFKTR's in-depth guide to Training high quality models

https://civitai.com/articles/397

I decided to add a debug "CHV3CPlane" token and a "CHV3CTiltRotor" token for the tiltrotor planes (because they are very different shapes) into each caption as well. These debug tokens work great for making unique planes as well. I also allowed for weighted captioning so those debug tokens, along with the plane type identifier tokens were weighted. For example a caption might look something like this:

"(Hawker Hunter), transonic jet-powered fighter aircraft, Hawker Aircraft, Royal Air Force (RAF), Avon turbojet engine, swept wing, (CHV3CPlane), a plane is flying in the air, swiss, low level, man, viewed in profile from far away, switzerland, illustration, overhead". 

After this long and patience testing process, I now had an acceptably decent dataset to begin training with.

Repeats:
I initially set the repeats for each folder to 5 but some plane types had a smaller amount of images in their dataset than others, so I did a rough balancing where the planes with a higher amount of images ran for 5 repeats, where as a set with few images might have ran for 10-15.

Training method:
I went about this project in a somewhat unorthodox way. For a dataset so big, I naturally had issues with overfitting. For LoHa a network dim of 8 is recommended but I changed over to 32 to allow for more training space. I went through a few phases trying to find the best settings that would allow me to train for more epochs before getting too burnt up. The original source model was v2-1_768-ema-pruned, however with each training run, I would merge the LoHa from the previous run into v2-1_768-ema-pruned and use that merge as the source model for the next run. The theory behind this is that it would gain some sort of extra knowledge from the previous run and give it a little bit of a head start. This theory needs more testing. Preferrably on a smaller dataset. After each training run, I would also merge the old source model that I merged with the new merged source model and then use that as the new source. I would also use Extract LyCORIS LoCON to extract a lora from it. This particular model is 4 LoHas from 4 different training runs (all on the same 71 plane dataset) merged together and extracted.

Training Specs:
I won't get too in the weeds with training specs. Instead I will post where I found the best settings to be for this particular project and point you to 3 other guides that go through everything in much better detail.

https://rentry.org/lora_train

RFKTR's in-depth guide to Training high quality models
https://civitai.com/articles/397

items.name: Cooler
items.description:
This character Lora works well on checkpoints that handles non human characters. Yet, with checkpoints that tend to cater to nonhuman characters and highly realistic looks, the results tend to be mutated.

The default strength for the Lora is what I would suggest to make sure the results closely matches the original look of the character. A Lora strength of 0.85 would give a Cooler themed style for characters, and a strength above 1 would result in messy images.

For trigger words beyond Cooler, listing the artists (art by Akira Toriyama:1), the artist behind the famous manga and anime, would help with better results. Also, the terms 'face mask' and 'white armor' helps as well due to the program thinking that the face mask area of Cooler is a mouth with clenched teeth for some reason.

The first version of this Lora is largely based on old screenshots of the Revenge of Cooler movie made in 2008, so I had not much to work with. I intend to find a way to make better screenshots or find better examples for this Lora for a nicer version 2.

For the rest of the stats, the usual default stats with DPM++ 2M Karras sampler makes for a good results with a checkpoint that works well with the Lora. This Lora also works very well with most of the tech Loras made by navimixu.

items.name: aZ-Fur6
items.description:
Just a checkpoint merge. Nothing extra fancy, and certainly not something that I can take credit for. All the hard work was done by others, I think I may have just found a decent balance between most furry models and real/semi-realism. I doubt that I could recreate this model if I tried. there were 6 different merges to get this result. 4 main models were used which include A-Zovya RPG Artist Tools, A-Zovya Photoreal, Crosskemono, & Furry Vixens.

Most anthro models are rather cartoonish, and usually realistic models just slap an animal head on a human body. At least that has been my experience with most of the models I use. I wanted to make a stab at rectifying that. Let me know how I did.

Please note that I wasn't aiming for 100% realism, but sometimes you get really lucky with the results.

modelVersions.name: Original (likely only)
modelVersions.description: Sometimes less is more. The goal is anthropomorphic but with a lot of realism influence. As such the more prompts you use to make the result more "humanoid" the more likely you are to get a human with animal ears. If this happens, work your prompt back and remove a few things that imply human like hair, breast size, specific clothing, etc.

items.name: Juliet Mills (1969-73 era - CHECKPOINT)
items.description:
THERE IS A LORA VERSION OF THIS MODEL AVAILABLE. IT IS EXACTLY THE SAME MODEL AS THIS ONE, EXCEPT IN A DIFFERENT AND LIGHTER FORMAT.

Shivam Dreambooth of British actress Juliet Mills, using 243 ref images and 1980 (real) reg images, for 20,000 steps.

The source material is mainly from the very end of the 1960s (Nanny and The Professor period), and the period for the Billy Wilder/Jack Lemmon film Avanti (around 1970), Mills' career high outside of TV work.

This model was trained on particularly high-quality data, with a wide range of poses, and is likely to perform well in pure T2I workflows, which is unusual, for my models:

I generally use these models in complex workflows, inpainting faces after initial T2Is, and using ControlNet extensively. So if you're hoping for one-click prompt magic, my models aren't data-curated with this in mind, but rather as tools for traditional workflows that use Photoshop and other older methods.

This model may produce subject-accurate NSFW output unless countered by negative prompts.

items.name: [GUIDE] Prompt Modifiers - "The Answer to the Great Question... Of Life, the Universe, and Everything
items.description:
... Is... Forty-two," said Deep Thought, with infinite majesty and calm.

  • The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy, Douglas Addams

note: It was intended for the article section, but the attachment exceeds the upload limit.

note: I'll add all the items to a new wildcards-set.

note: updated for SDXL, images generated with SDXLFaetastic

Disappointed?

Well quite disappointing, isn't it? Many people tried to quess why 42? Well simple answer: Addam Douglas want a number that sounds funny.
However, you have not clicked this quide for that, didn't you? I woundn't have, anyway.

Purpose

I've seen quite a few images and prompts over the few month and thought things like:

  • Whoa what a nice style!

  • How did they to THAT!

  • Why does it look so different from my generations?

Well I then check the prompt for detail. A thing I've found in many prompts were stuff like:

  • octane render

  • volumetric lighting

  • subsurface scattering

  • unreal engine etc.

What I want to summerize with this guide is a list of prompt modifiers (not sure it's the correct term, but it feel understandable). I did some "research" with my new friendly helper chatGPT, what kind of engines, rendering technics and art styles there are.

How does SD understand prompts and learns new stuff?

I'll try to summerize in easy words how I imagine SD understands prompts. For my student I explain it like this:

Imagine a child born, knowing nothing. However, from the first moment on it perceives it's surroundings. During the bounding it learns how its mother smells and the process continues. At some point it knows what a table is. Some thing with a plate and 4 legs. Let's call this state the base model of SD or SDXL. During finetuning this basemodel learns, that table can be a round coffee table, too. So it extends its knowledge of the table concept.

The neural network now associates with table not only 1 rectangular plate and 4 legs, but round shapes with 3 or even just 1 leg. It's "networked". During an example with a random prompt with my students (like each of them gives 1 word to the prompt) we had situation where we had cat and big in the prompt. As result we got 3 of 8 images with a tiger. How did that happen? Well my guess is cat is a feline, tiger is a feline and tiger is associated with big feline in the neural network. (At least thats my guess)

Comparing a neural network with an actual brain might real helps in analysing results of prompts. In a brain information is connected. Another example, look at the next person you see. What shape has the persons face? Your will use the concept of a 2 shape to describe the shape of the persons face. In one of my other guides I tried training style LoRAs only with shapes. It works! However, it works to well, because every image contains shapes, it can even be a perspective that looks triangular! So the concept is transported in different ways into the image. (check this guide of AIGARLIC, they made some basic training testings for LoRA) That made it really hard to get good results for persons sometimes. Fire was really challenging to train and in the end, face are still "made of fire" and get blurry or "flamed".

Next small example more related to training. Finetuning models give us creators endless possibilities. However, images used to train, push the model into the direction of input images subjects. So models trained on females are more likely to produce females, when the prompt is unspecfic, like "human" or "person".

Short example, my institution wants a project, where the students use generative AI, my fellow is teacher for history and would want Martin Luther as the main actor in the project. So I checked Dreamshaper 7 for Martin Luther, created image look mostly like the 2-3 images we have of him. No surpise, he's a celebritiy and "all" of his images are most likely part of SD1.5 base model. Putting him in a setting like a church portal in full body, well didn't work. It was just some monk with no resemblance of ML. So I tried prompting a monk looking like ML. With just monk and DS7 I got a female monk, beautiful!, but not ML. I tried to be more specific like, hair, eyes, double chin and MALE! Got a male monk, male, thin, beautiful, real handsome guy. Changed model to RPG5, got an buddhistic monk, well there might be more images of buddhistic monks than european monks. So models might prefer buddhistic monks over european monks.

I hope that these examples can help understanding better how our prompts work, without diving to deep into the technical layers.

With this "knowledge" you can assume that it depend on the models you use, if and how the following prompt modifiers work. I found that most of the words had the expected result in DS7 or SDXL Faetastic.

Some like Charmd or Super Natural were a bit primed by the TV-Series and a few other in a different meaning. ;)

42!

Finally 42, the answer to Life, the Universe, and Everything! Well seed 42. ❤️ As a fan of the Hitchhikers Guide to the Galaxy, there's only one option.

I use seed 42, with the x/y/z plot script, to make the images more comparable. Tried it with Dynamic Prompt wildcards, but it changes the seed.

Setup:

x: 42
y: ., house, car, woman
z: list of testing items

prompt house, .
Dreamshaper 7, 20 steps, cfg: 7, res: 640*832

Why this .? I wanted an image uninfluence by anything.

In the following chapters I'll only list the items tested.

  • as list

  • as comma separated list for x/y/z plot, if you want to test other models

  • I chose Dreamshaper, because like the model and it is really versatile

In the attachments you'll find a zip containing the results for each test:

  • grid

  • single images

If you have items, that are not in the list, leave a comment and I'll run it again, when I have. If you have another group of modifiers you want to see in this guide, let me know, too.

Be warned!

  1. The set contains some mature content! Can't be helped, since some engines or art styles, seem to be made for it.

  2. Have fun improving your prompts!

  3. Some items might be in multiple sets.

items.name: SDXL_fixedvae_fp16(Remove Watermark)
items.description:
This is merge model for:

1. 100% stable-diffusion-xl-base-1.0 and 100% stable-diffusion-xl-refine-1.0

https://huggingface.co/stabilityai/stable-diffusion-xl-base-1.0

https://huggingface.co/stabilityai/stable-diffusion-xl-refiner-1.0

2. sdxl-vae-fp16-fix

https://huggingface.co/madebyollin/sdxl-vae-fp16-fix

you can use this directly or finetune.

same license on stable-diffusion-xl-base-1.0

same vae license on sdxl-vae-fp16-fix

SDXL-VAE-FP16-Fix

SDXL-VAE-FP16-Fix is the SDXL VAE, but modified to run in fp16 precision without generating NaNs.

VAEDecoding in float32 / bfloat16 precisionDecoding in float16 precisionSDXL-VAE✅⚠️SDXL-VAE-FP16-Fix✅✅

Details

SDXL-VAE generates NaNs in fp16 because the internal activation values are too big:

SDXL-VAE-FP16-Fix was created by finetuning the SDXL-VAE to:

1. keep the final output the same, but

2. make the internal activation values smaller, by

3. scaling down weights and biases within the network

There are slight discrepancies between the output of SDXL-VAE-FP16-Fix and SDXL-VAE, but the decoded images should be close enough for most purposes.

Benchmark from here:by Kubuxu

https://huggingface.co/madebyollin/sdxl-vae-fp16-fix/discussions/7

Evaluation on COCO val-2017, 256x256, RandomCrop with padding
Metrics:
LPIPS: https://github.com/richzhang/PerceptualSimilarity/ (lower better) and structural similarity index measure via skimage.metrics (higher better)
Metrics given as: mean [79% credibility interval]

items.name: 200th Lora : Elmo for "Sesame Street"
items.description:
My 200th Lora ! If you like them, you can buy me beer here (https://ko-fi.com/djo226) or you can subscribe to my Patreon and get exclusive models (public showcase preview).

Elmo is a red Muppet character on the long-running children's television show Sesame Street. A furry red monster who speaks in a high-pitched falsetto voice and frequently refers to himself in the third person.

Prompt : Elmo, photography, trending on artstation, sharp focus, studio photo, intricate details, highly detailed, by greg rutkowski <lora:Elmo:0.7>

Negative prompt: (deformed iris, deformed pupils, semi-realistic, cgi, 3d, render, sketch, cartoon, drawing, anime, mutated hands and fingers:1.4), (deformed, distorted, disfigured:1.3), poorly drawn, bad anatomy, wrong anatomy, extra limb, missing limb, floating limbs, disconnected limbs, mutation, mutated, ugly, disgusting, amputation

Steps: 70, Sampler: DDIM, CFG scale: 12, Seed: -1, Face restoration: GFPGAN, Size: 768x1024, Model hash: 81086e2b3f, Model: realisticVisionV20_v20

Use Elmo as trigger.
